# Decision Making with IF 🚦

The simplest decision logic.

## Syntax
```c
if (condition) {
    // code to execute if condition is true
}
```

## Example
```c
int score = 85;
if (score > 50) {
    printf("You passed!\n");
}
```
If `score` was 40, nothing would be printed.

# Two or More Paths 🛣️

## If-Else
Handle both True and False cases.
```c
if (age >= 18) {
    printf("Adult");
} else {
    printf("Minor");
}
```

## Else-If Ladder
Check multiple conditions in sequence.
```c
if (marks >= 90) {
    printf("Grade A");
} else if (marks >= 80) {
    printf("Grade B");
} else {
    printf("Grade C");
}
```

# Multi-Way Branching: Switch 🎛️

A cleaner alternative to many `else-if`s when checking a single variable against multiple constants.

```c
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // code
        break;
    case value2:
        // code
        break;
    default:
        // default code
}
```

> ⚠️ **Important:** Don't forget the `break;` statement! Without it, execution "falls through" to the next case automatically.

# Looping: While 🔁

Repeats code as long as a condition is true.

**Syntax:**
```c
while (condition) {
    // code
}
```

**Example:**
```c
int i = 1;
while (i <= 5) {
    printf("%d ", i);
    i++; // Don't forget to update i!
}
```
If you forget `i++`, the condition never becomes false -> **Infinite Loop!** ♾️

# Looping: Do-While ↩️

Similar to `while`, but guarantees the code runs **at least once**.

**Syntax:**
```c
do {
    // code
} while (condition);
```

**Example:**
```c
int i = 10;
do {
    printf("%d", i);
} while (i < 5);
```
Output: `10` (Even though `10 < 5` is false, it prints once before checking).

# Looping: For 🔄

The most compact loop. Good when you know the number of iterations.

**Syntax:**
```c
for (initialization; condition; update) {
    // code
}
```

**Example:**
```c
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    printf("Iteration %d\n", i);
}
```
All loop control connection logic is in one line!

# Jump Statements 🦘

## Break
Exits the loop (or switch) immediately.
```c
for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i == 5) break; // Stops when i is 5
    printf("%d ", i);
}
// Output: 0 1 2 3 4
```

## Continue
Skips the *current* iteration and jumps to the next one.
```c
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    if (i == 2) continue; // Skips 2
    printf("%d ", i);
}
// Output: 0 1 3 4
```

# Putting it Together 🧩

Let's build a mini calculator using `switch` and `while`.

